Stratifying

To see if gender affects whether a person earns more than 50K, letâs stratify by gender and compare earnings.

suppressPackageStartupMessages(require(dplyr))
t1 <- mydata1 |> 
  group_by(sex) |> 
  summarise(
    less_than_50K = mean(income == "<=50K") * 100, 
    more_than_50K = mean(income == ">50K") *100
  ) %>%
  as.data.frame()

print(t1)
      sex less_than_50K more_than_50K
1  Female             0             0
2    Male             0             0

result: 89% of female adults earn less than 50K while about 69% of male adults earn less than 50K. While there might be other confounding variables, this analysis suggests that female adults are more likely to earn less than 50K compared to adult men.

Visualizing this:

library(ggplot2)

ggplot(t1, aes(x = sex)) +
  geom_bar(aes(y = less_than_50K, fill = "Less than 50K"), stat = "identity", position = position_dodge(width = 0.8)) + geom_bar(aes(y = more_than_50K, fill = "More than 50K"), stat = "identity", position = position_dodge(width = 0.8))+
  labs(x= "Gender", y = "Percentage", fill = "Income Level") +
  ggtitle("Income Distribution by Gender") +
  theme_minimal()

Diving deeper into variables

Since hours-per-week is not consistent across people, and this may be affecting income, letâs filter the data set and only focus on people who work 40 hours a week.

Marital status and Income

Letâs explore whether marital status have a relationship with income.

library(dplyr)
forty_hrs_week_data <- mydata1 %>% 
  filter(`hours-per-week` == 40)

t2 <- forty_hrs_week_data %>% 
  group_by(`marital-status`, income) %>%
  summarise(count = n()) %>%
  mutate(percentage = count / sum(count) * 100)
`summarise()` has grouped output by 'marital-status'. You can override using
the `.groups` argument.
tail(t2)
# A tibble: 6 Ã 4
# Groups:   marital-status [3]
  `marital-status` income   count percentage
  <chr>            <chr>    <int>      <dbl>

2 " Never-married" " >50K"    171       3.59

ggplot(t2, aes(x = `marital-status`, y = percentage, fill = income)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = "dodge") +
  labs(x = "Marital Status", y = "Percentage", fill = "Income Level") +
  ggtitle("Income Distribution by Marital Status (40 Hours per Week)") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

result: according to our visualization, adult females that are married either with armed forces spouse or civilian spouse tend to earn more than 50K more than women that are divorced, widowed, separated, or never married. Thus, this plot shows that the marital status does have a significant impact on income level.

Education_num and Income

library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)

t3 <- forty_hrs_week_data %>%
  group_by(`education-num`, income)%>%
  summarise(count = n()) %>%
  mutate(percentage = count / sum(count) *100)

result: We can see that as education level (education_num score) increases, the % of people who >50K is increasing. There is a strong correlation between income level and education level.

Summarizing data types and visualization:

Because the variables we compared were categorical, we created bar plots. But, now letâs explore continuous variable and create histograms.

Age and Income

library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)

ggplot(forty_hrs_week_data, aes(x = age, fill = income)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 1, position = "dodge", alpha = 0.6) +
  facet_wrap(~ sex) +
  labs(x = "Age", y = "Count", fill = "Income Level") +
  ggtitle("Distribution of Age and Income Level by Gender (40 Hours per Week)") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

result: In both cases, lower income level distribution is extremely skewed to the right, suggesting that as age increases, the number of lower income people decreases (basically income increases).

Conclusion

We analyzed public data set called adult.data and cleaned to perform analysis. We stratified by several variables to identify relationships between them, specifically relationship with income level. We also paid attention to what visualization to use on what type of data and were able to answer our questions.
